## Error Handling in Rust

Rust has no exceptions. Errors are **values** — represented by `Result<T, E>` and `Option<T>`:

```rust
enum Result<T, E> {
    Ok(T),    // Success with value
    Err(E),   // Error with details
}

enum Option<T> {
    Some(T),  // Value exists
    None,     // Value is absent (like null, but safe)
}
```

### The ? Operator

`?` is syntactic sugar for 'if this is Err, return the error immediately':

```rust
// Without ?:
fn get_port() -> Result<u16, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let config = match fs::read_to_string("config.txt") {
        Ok(s) => s,
        Err(e) => return Err(Box::new(e)),
    };
    let port = match config.trim().parse::<u16>() {
        Ok(p) => p,
        Err(e) => return Err(Box::new(e)),
    };
    Ok(port)
}

// With ?:
fn get_port() -> Result<u16, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let config = fs::read_to_string("config.txt")?;
    let port: u16 = config.trim().parse()?;
    Ok(port)
}
```

### Why Not unwrap()?

`unwrap()` panics on error — the thread crashes with no recovery. Use it only in:
- Tests (`#[test]` functions)
- Prototypes (not production code)
- Cases where failure is truly impossible

### Option — Null Done Right

Rust has no null. `Option<T>` forces you to handle the None case:

```rust
fn find_user(id: u32) -> Option<User> {
    users.iter().find(|u| u.id == id).cloned()
}

match find_user(42) {
    Some(user) => println!("Found: {}", user.name),
    None => println!("User not found"),
}
```

expandableSections.content:
Both `Result` and `Option` have powerful combinators:

```rust
// Map the success value:
let port: Result<u16, _> = config.parse::<u16>().map(|p| p + 1000);

// Chain fallible operations:
let user = find_user(42)
    .and_then(|u| verify_active(u))
    .map(|u| u.name)
    .unwrap_or(String::from("anonymous"));

// Provide default:
let port = config.parse::<u16>().unwrap_or(8080);
```

