## Iterating with Ownership

Rust has three ways to iterate, corresponding to the three forms of access:

| Syntax | Method | Yields | Ownership |
|--------|--------|--------|----------|
| `for x in vec` | `.into_iter()` | `T` | Consumes the vector |
| `for x in &vec` | `.iter()` | `&T` | Borrows immutably |
| `for x in &mut vec` | `.iter_mut()` | `&mut T` | Borrows mutably |

```rust
let names = vec!["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"];

// Borrow — vector is still usable after:
for name in &names {
    println!("{}", name);  // name is &str
}
println!("Count: {}", names.len()); // Fine!

// Mutate — modify elements in place:
let mut scores = vec![85, 92, 78];
for score in &mut scores {
    *score += 10;  // Dereference to modify
}

// Consume — take ownership of each element:
for name in names {
    expensive_processing(name);  // name is String (owned)
}
// names is now empty/invalid
```

### Iterator Adapters

Rust's iterator adapters are zero-cost abstractions — they compile to the same machine code as hand-written loops:

```rust
let sum: i32 = numbers.iter()
    .filter(|&&n| n > 0)
    .map(|&n| n * 2)
    .sum();
```

`.iter()` borrows, so `numbers` is still valid after. `.into_iter()` would consume it.

expandableSections.content:
`.collect()` transforms an iterator into any collection. The 'turbofish' (`::<>`) tells Rust which collection:

```rust
let evens: Vec<i32> = (0..100).filter(|n| n % 2 == 0).collect();
// or with turbofish:
let evens = (0..100).filter(|n| n % 2 == 0).collect::<Vec<_>>();

// Collect into other types:
use std::collections::HashSet;
let unique: HashSet<_> = names.iter().collect();

// Collect Result<Vec<T>, E> from Vec<Result<T, E>>:
let parsed: Result<Vec<i32>, _> = ["1", "2", "x"]
    .iter().map(|s| s.parse::<i32>()).collect();
// Err(ParseIntError) — stops at first error
```

